We can also directly measure the dissociation time upon a rupture event at 
 F
 test. The dissociation time before each rupture event, 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}$\Delta t$\end{document}
 , indicated the kinetic barrier and local stability for TRF1 unbinding. Kramer Bell-Evans model says that the kinetic rate 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}$k$\end{document}
  for dissociation is a function of force 
 F, i.e., 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}$k = \frac{1}{{\langle \tau \rangle }} = {k_0}{\rm{exp}}( {\frac{{F{x^\dagger }}}{{{k_B}T}}} )$\end{document}
 , where 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}${x^\dagger }$\end{document}
  is the activation distance from the TRF1 bound state to the transition state, and 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}${k_0}$\end{document}
  is the extrapolated TRF1 dissociating rate at 
 F = 0 pN. At [TRF1] = 10 nM, we measured the dependence of the averaged dissociation time, 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}$\langle \tau \rangle$\end{document}
 , at various 
 F
 test (
 Supplementary Figure S4 and Figure 
 3D, inset). Evaluated by Kramer's model above, we found that the logarithm of 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}$k$\end{document}
  linearly responds to the testing forces of 2–8 pN (Figure 
 3D, red). The estimated 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}${x^\dagger }$\end{document}
  is 0.7 nm, ∼ 2 bp between the TRF1 bound telomeric complex and the activated state for a rupture event. The dissociation rate 

  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{upgreek} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} }{}$k$\end{document}
  at zero force is 0.04 s
 −1, corresponding to 23 s for the dissociation time upon a rupture event at 
 F = 0 pN.
